  "text": "You’ll love the sweet and tart Pomegranate Martini. It’s a cousin to the Cosmo mixed with pomegranate juice instead of cranberry juice. This is a great drink for your Thanksgiving menu or holiday party! It’s festive and delicious. More cocktail ideas: Old Fashioned, Manhattan, French 75, Kir Royale, Vieux Carré, Pink Squirrel, Paper Plane. Ingredients in a Pomegranate Martini Pomegranate Juice – Sweet, tart juice. Store-bought or fresh squeezed will both work great for this recipe. Vodka – Choose a quality, unflavored vodka. Orange Liqueur – Such as triple-sec, Cointreau or Grand Marnier. Lemon Juice – Fresh squeezed lemon juice adds so much depth to this recipe. The best glassware to serve this drink in is a classic martini glass. Instructions Begin by adding pomegranate juice, vodka, orange liqueur and lemon juice to a cocktail shaker half filled with ice. Shake for 10-15 seconds until well chilled. Strain and pour into a martini glass (bonus points for using a chilled glass). Garnish with a lemon twist or a sprig of fresh rosemary. Tips for Making To chill a martini glass, simply place it in the freezer for at least 30 minutes. This will make it nice and frosty. Remove it when you’re ready to serve your cocktail. You can garnish the drink with fresh pomegranate seeds or even a wedge of pomegranate fruit if you like. This recipe makes the perfect holiday drink because pomegranate juice is more pigmented and makes a bright red color much more intense than cranberry juice (such as a Cosmopolitan) while tasting very similar. Garnishing with fresh rosemary sprigs adds to the holiday appeal. If you don’t have lemon juice, you can also use another citrus juice such as lime juice in its place. To make a pitcher recipe, increase this recipe for 6 servings. Serve in a pitcher with frozen cranberries to keep it chilled. Don’t add ice to the pitcher. Try a sugar rim for a festive look. Frequently Asked QuestionsWhat is in a pomegranate martini? The ingredients in a pomegranate martini are pomegranate juice, vodka, orange liqueur and fresh lemon juice. How to make a pomegranate martini? Begin by adding pomegranate juice, vodka, orange liqueur and lemon juice to a cocktail shaker half filled with ice. Shake for 10-15 seconds until well chilled. Strain and pour into a martini glass (bonus points for using a chilled glass). Garnish with a lemon twist or a sprig of fresh rosemary. More Recipes to Try Classic Cocktail – Grasshopper, Gimlet, Aviation Cocktail Appetizer Ideas – 20 Easy Party Appetizers Dessert Ideas – Christmas Desserts Get our FREE recipe guide with our most popular recipes of all time!Get the Guide Ingredients ▢ 1½ ounces vodka ▢ 1 ounce pomegranate juice ▢ ¾ ounce lemon juice ▢ ½ ounce orange liqueur ▢ 1 cocktail shaker▢ 1 martini glass Instructions Begin by adding pomegranate juice, vodka, orange liqueur and lemon juice to a cocktail shaker half filled with ice.Shake for 10-15 seconds until well chilled.Strain and pour into a martini glass (bonus points for using a chilled glass).Garnish with a lemon twist or a sprig of fresh rosemary. To chill a martini glass, simply place it in the freezer for at least 30 minutes. This will make it nice and frosty. Remove it when you’re ready to serve your cocktail. You can garnish the drink with fresh pomegranate seeds or even a wedge of pomegranate fruit if you like. This recipe makes the perfect holiday drink because pomegranate juice is more pigmented and makes a bright red color much more intense than cranberry juice (such as a Cosmopolitan) while tasting very similar. Garnishing with fresh rosemary sprigs adds to the holiday appeal. If you don’t have lemon juice, you can also use another citrus juice such as lime juice in its place. To make a pitcher recipe, increase this recipe for 6 servings. Serve in a pitcher with frozen cranberries to keep it chilled. Don’t add ice to the pitcher. Try a sugar rim for a festive look. Nutrition FactsPomegranate MartiniAmount per Serving% Daily Value** Percent Daily Values are based on a 2000 calorie diet.Notice: Nutrition is auto-calculated, using Spoonacular, for your convenience. Where relevant, we recommend using your own nutrition calculations.",
